<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-299-338  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 299 338.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>EDN  March 23 1989 v34 6A p62(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Medical electronics melds technology and altruism: hiring outlookat most companies is healthy.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Stenzler-Centonze, Marjorie.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Demand for electronics engineers in the medical industry willcontinue to be strong in 1989.andP;  The key attractions to working inthe medical-electronics industry is that engineers can see thedirect influence they have on human life and they have theopportunity to work closely with researchers and healthcareprofessionals.andP;  Boehringer Mannheim Corp, a developer of medicaldiagnostic equipment, orthopedic devices and biotechnology, plansto hire 25 engineers in 1989.andP;  The company seeks electrical andchemical engineers as well as engineers experienced inelectro-optics.andP;  General Electric's Medical Systems Group, makerof diagnostic imaging products, expects to hire 100 engineers in1989 with backgrounds in computer science, hardware and software,signal and digital-signal processing, and image-analysisengineering.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Boehringer Mannheim Corp. (recruiting)General Electric Co. GE Medical Systems (recruiting).andO;Topic:     Employment OpportunityHiringElectronic IndustryMedical Issues.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>